### MIT Coil Set {#sec-mit-coils}

- **1x TX coil + 1x RX coil** wound on ferrite cores
- **Ferrite cores:** 6-8 mm diameter x 40-80 mm long **(Target)**
- **Mounting:** Glued along rod (not in bulky head) for streamlined profile
- **Orientation:** Orthogonal or slightly separated to reduce direct coupling
- **Wire:** Fine wire (34-38 AWG), 200-400 turns **(Modeled)** for adequate signal strength

### ERT-Lite Rings {#sec-ert-rings}

- **2-3 narrow ring electrodes** (3-5 mm wide bands) **(Target)**
- **Standard positions:** 0.5 m and 1.5 m from tip **(Target)**
- **Deep extension:** Add third ring at 2.5-3.0 m **(Target)** for longer rods
- **Material:** Stainless steel or copper foil
- **Mounting:** Bonded with epoxy, flush with rod surface

### Rod Construction {#sec-rod-construction}

- **Material:** Fiberglass (G10) or carbon-fiber segments
- **OD:** 10-16 mm **(Target)** (target: 16 mm with flush joints)
- **Segments:** 50 cm or 100 cm lengths with M12x1.75 threaded couplers **(Target)**
- **Total depth:** Up to 3 m **(Target)** with coupled segments
- **Weight:** ~50-100 g per meter **(Modeled)** (much lighter than 25mm design)

::: {#cell-fig-component-positioning .cell fig-height='5' fig-width='10' execution_count=2}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Component positioning along a 3-meter (Target) probe assembly. Sensors are distributed to maximize coverage: TX coil near surface for strong drive, RX coil at mid-depth, and ERT rings at three depths for resistivity profiling. Threaded joints allow field disassembly for transport.](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-component-positioning-output-1.png){#fig-component-positioning}
:::
:::


## Central Electronics Hub {#sec-electronics-hub}

All active electronics reside in a central hub unit, typically housed in a rugged IP65-rated enclosure. This centralized architecture simplifies probe design, reduces per-probe cost, and enables sophisticated signal processing that would be impractical in distributed electronics.

::: {#cell-fig-hub-layout .cell fig-height='7' fig-width='10' execution_count=3}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Central Electronics Hub internal layout. The hub contains power supply, MCU (ESP32 or STM32), MIT analog front-end (DDS transmitter and lock-in receiver), ERT current source and measurement circuitry, and the high-density analog multiplexer array. DB25 connectors provide interface to Zone Hub trunk cables.](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-hub-layout-output-1.png){#fig-hub-layout}
:::
:::


### MIT Driver/Receiver {#sec-mit-electronics}

- **Central DDS sine source** (AD9833) for 2-50 kHz operation **(Manufacturer spec)** --- generates the reference waveform for both TX drive and lock-in demodulation
- **TX driver amplifier** (OPA2186 buffer) --- zero-drift precision op-amp with 90 uA quiescent current **(Manufacturer spec)** drives all probe TX coils via trunk cables at 10-50 mA **(Target)**
- **RX low-noise amplifier chain** (AD8421 instrumentation amplifier) --- 3 nV/$\sqrt{\text{Hz}}$ input noise **(Manufacturer spec)**, G=1000 **(Target)**, followed by second-stage gain (INA128) for total chain gain of 800-1000x **(Target)**
- **ADC/lock-in detection** (AD7124-8 integrated AFE) --- 24-bit sigma-delta ADC with programmable gain **(Manufacturer spec)**, digital synchronous demodulation extracts in-phase and quadrature components
- **MCU** (ESP32 or STM32) for control, DSP, and data acquisition

For detailed component specifications, comparison tables, and PCB implementation guidance, see [Electronics](../build-guide/electronics.qmd).

### ERT System {#sec-ert-electronics}

- **Howland current source** - 0.5-2 mA **(Target)**, programmable via DAC, output impedance >1 M-ohm **(Target)**
- **Polarity reversal** - H-bridge for DC measurements with polarity cycling every 1-2 seconds **(Target)** to cancel electrode polarization
- **Voltage measurement** - differential amplifier (INA128) + AD7124-8 24-bit ADC **(Manufacturer spec)** --- shared ADC with MIT channel via multiplexer
- **Multiplexer** - High-density matrix (CD74HC4067 16:1) **(Manufacturer spec)** to switch electrode pairs, supporting 80+ channels **(Target)**

### Power and Communications {#sec-power-comms}

- **Power:** 12V or 5V battery pack, 10-20 Ah **(Target)** for full-day field operations
- **Distribution:** Power remains at hub; only signals traverse trunk cables
- **Data logging:** USB or WiFi connection to field tablet
- **Control:** Centralized MCU handles all scheduling and sequencing

## System Block Diagram {#sec-block-diagram}

The complete HIRT system follows a hierarchical architecture: Central Electronics Hub connects to multiple Zone Hubs via high-density trunk cables, with each Zone Hub serving as a passive breakout for 4 individual probes. This scalable design supports arrays from 4 probes (single zone) to 50+ probes **(Target)** (12+ zones).

::: {#cell-fig-system-block .cell fig-height='7' fig-width='11' execution_count=4}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![HIRT system block diagram showing the hierarchical architecture. The Central Electronics Hub contains all active circuitry. High-density trunk cables (DB25) connect to passive Zone Hubs, which distribute signals to individual probes. This architecture minimizes cable complexity while maintaining signal integrity over 10-20m (Target) cable runs.](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-system-block-output-1.png){#fig-system-block}
:::
:::


## Scalability Architecture: The Zone Strategy {#sec-zone-strategy}

To scale the system from a small prototype (4-8 probes) to a field-ready array (20-50+ probes) without creating an unmanageable cable harness, HIRT employs a **Zone Wiring Strategy**. This approach divides the array into logical zones, each containing 4 probes connected through a local Zone Hub.

### The Challenge {#sec-zone-challenge}

A single passive probe requires 8-12 analog conductors **(Target)** (TX coil pair, RX coil pair, 3x ERT rings, Shield, ID). Connecting 25 probes directly to a central hub would require terminating ~250-300 conductors **(Modeled)** at a single panel, creating severe mechanical congestion and crosstalk risks.

### The Solution: Passive Zone Hubs {#sec-zone-solution}

1. **Probes connect to a local Zone Hub:** A small, passive IP65 box placed on the ground near the probe cluster.
2. **Zone Hubs connect to the Main Unit:** Via a single high-quality, shielded trunk cable (DB25 or 37-pin connector).
3. **Central Hub manages Zones:** The hub switches between trunk lines to address specific probes via the multiplexer array.

::: {#cell-fig-zone-topology .cell fig-height='6' fig-width='10' execution_count=5}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Zone Hub wiring topology. Each passive Zone Hub aggregates connections from 4 probes into a single DB25 trunk cable. Terminal blocks inside the Zone Hub provide strain relief and easy field replacement of individual probe cables. This modular approach dramatically simplifies field deployment.](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-zone-topology-output-1.png){#fig-zone-topology}
:::
:::


::: {#cell-fig-trunk-cable .cell fig-height='6' fig-width='10' execution_count=6}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Trunk cable DB25 pin assignments for a 4-probe zone. Each probe uses 7 conductors (TX pair, RX pair, 3 ERT rings), with shared shield and zone ID pins. Shielded twisted-pair cables maintain signal integrity over 10-20m (Target) runs from Zone Hub to Central Hub.](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-trunk-cable-output-1.png){#fig-trunk-cable}
:::
:::


::: {.callout-note}
## Zone Wiring Benefits & Noise Immunity

- **Modular Deployment:** Setup involves running a few thick cables rather than dozens of thin ones
- **Signal Integrity:** Trunk cables utilize individual shielded twisted pairs for all analog lines
- **Noise Rejection:** Differential signaling (balanced TX drive, instrumentation amp RX) rejects common-mode noise
- **Field Repair:** A damaged probe cable only affects one local zone, not the main harness
- **Scalability:** Add zones as needed without redesigning the core system
:::

## Signal Flow Paths {#sec-signal-flow}

### MIT Signal Path {#sec-mit-signal-path}

The MIT measurement chain begins with the MCU commanding the AD9833 DDS to generate a sine wave at the selected frequency (2-50 kHz). The DDS output passes through the OPA2186 buffer amplifier, which provides rail-to-rail drive to the TX coil via the trunk cable. The induced signal in the RX coil passes through the AD8421 low-noise preamplifier (3 nV/$\sqrt{\text{Hz}}$), then through a second gain stage (INA128) before the AD7124-8 ADC performs synchronous demodulation to extract amplitude and phase information.

::: {#cell-fig-mit-signal-flow .cell fig-height='4' fig-width='11' execution_count=7}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![MIT signal flow from DDS generation through TX drive and RX amplification. The lock-in detection uses the reference signal from the DDS to perform synchronous demodulation, extracting both in-phase (resistive) and quadrature (reactive) components. Operating frequency range: 2-50 kHz (Manufacturer spec).](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-mit-signal-flow-output-1.png){#fig-mit-signal-flow}
:::
:::


### ERT Signal Path {#sec-ert-signal-path}

The ERT system injects a known current (0.5-2 mA) **(Target)** between selected electrode pairs and measures the resulting voltage distribution. A Howland current source provides stable injection regardless of load impedance (output impedance >1 M-ohm), while the INA128 differential amplifier rejects common-mode noise from the measurement electrodes. The AD7124-8 ADC is shared between MIT and ERT channels via the CD74HC4067 multiplexer array.

::: {#cell-fig-ert-signal-flow .cell fig-height='4.5' fig-width='11' execution_count=8}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![ERT signal flow showing current injection and voltage measurement paths. The Howland current source provides output impedance >1M ohm (Target), ensuring stable injection regardless of electrode contact resistance. Polarity reversal (every 1-2 seconds) (Target) cancels electrode polarization effects.](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-ert-signal-flow-output-1.png){#fig-ert-signal-flow}
:::
:::


## Multiplexer Switching Topology {#sec-mux-topology}

The analog multiplexer array is central to HIRT's ability to address any probe in the array. Using CD74HC4067 16:1 analog multiplexers, the system can route TX drive signals to any probe's TX coil and simultaneously route any RX coil to the receiver chain. Similar switching enables flexible ERT electrode pair selection.

::: {#cell-fig-mux-topology .cell fig-height='7' fig-width='10' execution_count=9}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Multiplexer switching topology showing channel allocation across MIT and ERT subsystems. The MCU controls all MUX address lines, enabling any-to-any probe addressing. Total capacity: 80+ analog channels (Target) (32 MIT + 48+ ERT) using cascaded 16:1 multiplexers (Manufacturer spec).](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-mux-topology-output-1.png){#fig-mux-topology}
:::
:::


## Array Configuration Options {#sec-array-configurations}

The HIRT system supports multiple array geometries optimized for different investigation scenarios. Array configuration affects both lateral resolution and the distribution of ray paths through the target volume. The following standard configurations address common field requirements.

::: {#cell-fig-array-configs .cell fig-height='4' fig-width='11' execution_count=10}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Standard array configuration options. (a) Square grid provides uniform coverage for unknown target locations. (b) Perimeter array enables safe standoff from suspected UXO while maintaining imaging capability. (c) Dense center configuration concentrates probes around a known anomaly for maximum resolution.](architecture_files/figure-html/fig-array-configs-output-1.png){#fig-array-configs}
:::
:::


| Configuration | Best For | Probe Count | Spacing |
|---------------|----------|-------------|---------|
| Square Grid | Unknown target locations | 16-36 (4x4 to 6x6) | 1.5-2.0 m (Target) |
| Perimeter | UXO/hazard standoff | 12-16 | 1.5-2.0 m (Target) |
| Dense Center | Known anomaly detail | 17-25 | 0.75-1.0 m center (Target) |

